In the botanical department of the Naturhistoriska Riks- museet (Stockholm) the author has during the last two years looked for plants from Linne and has succeeded in collecting a considerable number. They have been found for the most part amongst bundles of plants and in cases from old times (the latter part of the 18th century). which in the course of years (presumably about 1860) had been packed away in lumbenrooms, owing to want of space, and were of course bound to suffer injury from (11151, 5001, damu and insects. Thanks however 10 1110 indestructable paper and the old method of gluing the whole plant fast, these old specimens are comparatively well preserved, and many plants look as if they had been quite recently prepared.

These are precious treasures from the great epoch 01 our natural history, which are thus again brought to light. Lin- naeus himself has laid stress on the importance 01 possessing material which might serve as a control in case a fresh in- vestigation should be required, and especially with regard to his own plants and original specimens 1101135 uttered the following words: »Ovarderliga i sig sjalfva, med tiden mer och mer begarliga›>.² He clearly realized that his life and activity had been intimately bound up with the whole future development 01 botany. His collections are still in demand and are eonstantly being consulted not merely as relics from the time when the »princeps botanicorum» himself was living in the realm of Flora, but 35 1110 111051 reliable aid to the study of his writings and as being as it were answers out of his own mouth to vexed botanical questions.
